Text.Value: Rest. Heal. Celebrate if you wish. Mourn if you must. Come morning, we shall discuss delivering you from your parasite.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'We've been through a lot. Take some time to gather yourself'

Text.Value: You will stay, as a novice anew. You have forgotten the ways of the druids, the natural order of things.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dispensing punishment

Text.Value: The grove is nature's beating heart - I was glad to help save it.
I acted to save my kin, not this place.
I hope this grove of yours is worth the bloodshed.
How is this possible...?
The grove stands. Nature prevails. I owe you my thanks - and an introduction.
Misplaced, self-important concern. She must learn to respect the balance of all things. But the grove still needs her.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining his lenient treatment of Kagha

Text.Value: So as you say, and so it is done, Master.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Bows and steps back from Halsin
EditorData.NodeContext: Kagha accepts her punishment offers a slight bow and retreats from Halsin

Text.Value: Well done? No... this shouldn't have been necessary in the first place. I failed.
As for what you've done for the grove, speak to Rath. He will see to your reward.
Is such mercy wise? She's strayed from your teachings once already.
As you wish, Master Halsin.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: She gives a reluctant bow and retreats from Halsin
EditorData.NodeContext: Not happy. Said through clenched teeth. She gives a reluctant bow and retreats from Halsin

Text.Value: I'm sorry to say, I can't undo that magic. I can't cure you. But that doesn't mean I can't help.
The grove is nature's beating heart - I was glad to help save it.
I acted to save my kin, not this place.
I did as I wished to. I never cared if this place was saved or not.
This place means nothing to me, but a great deal to you, it seems. I hope the blood price was worth it.
I hope this grove of yours was worth the bloodshed.
What happens next?
A child died because of her? She deserved far worse than that.
Perhaps... but I wouldn't want to place all my faith in blind luck.
Nature will determine your fate - whatever happens to you next, know that it is the Oak Father's will.
You show no pity, no remorse. I cannot absolve you.
It would have been easier if you just died, Kagha. Now I have to hear your excuses instead.
Grace is bestowed by nature, not me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stern

Text.Value: Are you mad? Kagha's a traitor.
You overreacted. The child's death was an accident.
I owe you nothing. Goblins swarmed us like roaches while you stumbled after the past.

EditorData.NodeContext: Defiant

Text.Value: There is no we. You were the driving force behind this madness. Now it stops.
I escaped from an illithid ship after being infected. Maybe the process was interrupted.
I will allow you to stay. But consider yourself a novice anew. You have forgotten the ways of the druids - our place in the natural order.

EditorData.NodeContext: Outlining her punishment

Text.Value: She knows now what cavorting in the shadows brings her. She will not stray again. Besides, this is no time to lose a promising druid.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining his lenient treatment of Kagha

Text.Value: Yes. I have a mind flayer parasite inside my head. I want your help removing it.
You're welcome. What now?
I was going to show leniency, but Kagha... a child is dead because of you.
An error most grave, Master. I beg your grace.

EditorData.NodeContext: Contrite

Text.Value: A dreadful misdeed - one she will never live down. But the grove still needs her passion.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining his reasoning to the player

Text.Value: No need to be so harsh. Kagha acted out of concern.
You were too lenient. There's bad blood between tieflings and druids because of her.
Kagha had that coming to her. Well done.
Enough. If anyone befouled this place, it is you - by sowing division, hatred - death.
You are an enemy of nature, to be shunned until you redeem yourself or die. Now go.
The girl's parents should have decided your fate, but they perished. Instead, nature will judge you.
Leave.
No doubt you'd have me flay her or cast her into a spiked pit. But the grove needs druids.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining his lenient treatment of Kagha

Text.Value: Apologies for that ugliness. A more bitter homecoming than I would have wished, but at least the grove stands, thanks to you.
Consider it in the past now. We must look forward.
I watched that child die because of her. She deserved far worse than that.
Such mercy is a show of weakness. You're tainting a hard-won victory.
Kagha did not act alone - I found evidence that she conspired with Shadow Druids.
Kagha was not acting on her own - she was under the influence of Shadow Druids.
I cannot absolve you, even if you are repentant.
What about my problem? I need help.
You will soon see why. But enough of that for now - I owe you my thanks.

EditorData.NodeContext: There's a little foreboding hidden in these phrases. A lot hinges on what he'll tell us tomorrow.

Text.Value: Take tonight to rest, recuperate -celebrate. Tomorrow, I'll join your camp so I can help with the trials yet to come.
The grove stands. Nature prevails. And again, I am in your debt.

EditorData.logicalname: DIDN'T MEET HALSIN IN GOB CAMP

Text.Value: A thief is dead - she stole the idol, befouled the grove!
Tomorrow morning, we shall discuss what is to come.

EditorData.NodeContext: This is a much anticipated converation that he's aluding to.

Text.Value: ...It's true. I can feel it right now. Oak Father preserve you, child.
I am Halsin - First Druid of the Emerald Grove... and I sense you have a problem you seek my help with.

EditorData.NodeContext: Knowing - referring to the player's tadpole problem

Text.Value: If only you had come to this place in more peaceful times. You'd have been a welcome addition.
And yet save it you did. I am grateful no matter what your motivations.
Believe me, it is. The span of a mortal life isn't enough to grasp the importance of this place. Its roots touch everything.
You took it upon yourself to undertake the Rite of Thorns? To spill blood in this sacred place?

EditorData.NodeContext: Reading the riot act to Kagha

Text.Value: It was an accident! She stole the idol - we were overzealous, yes, but -
I don't know.
I don't know what you mean. What problem?
There is naught a clear and meditative mind cannot overcome. After we stray, we return to the fold, having learnt to do better. And in the fold, Kagha is needed.
Speak to Rath - he will reward you for your efforts.

EditorData.NodeContext: Referring to one of his underlings

Text.Value: You shall learn it all once again, right here. Backslide, and nature's fury will crush you.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Shape up or ship out'

Text.Value: You are an enemy of nature, to be shunned until you redeem yourself or die. Now go.
You took it upon yourself to undertake the Rite of Thorns? I ought to exile you from this place. Forever.

EditorData.NodeContext: Reading the riot act to Kagha

Text.Value: Silence. The rite has been ended.

EditorData.NodeContext: Forceful. He's heard enough from her.

Text.Value: Someone is using very powerful magic to modify these tadpoles. They are using them to exert control over the infected.
That's all? She tried to imprison a child.
Take tonight to rest, recuperate - celebrate. Tomorrow, we can strike out.

EditorData.logicalname: ALREADY SAID HE'D JOIN CAMP TOMORROW

Text.Value: It's no coincidence that we found each other, I'll wager? You're after a cure for this parasite.
Wait - how did you get here?

EditorData.AnimationTags: KAGHA backs away from Halsin and leaves. [CodyM]
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Kagha slinks away after Halsin condemns her, He watches her go, before acknowledging the player, his temper softening.

Text.Value: At the goblin camp, I hoped to find a way to remove the tadpoles. I failed - but I did find the next best thing. I found out where they come from.
Spilled blood will not right bad blood. Allow me to deal with my own - I still have need of her.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining his lenient treatment of Kagha

Text.Value: You chose to abandon us. I chose to protect us!

EditorData.NodeContext: Defiant

Text.Value: Her punishment is only just beginning, trust me.
It is up to you to prove the lessons have been learned once more.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'I hope you've learned your lesson'

Text.Value: You are banished from this place - banished from everywhere the Oak Father's creations thrive.
Please. Don't sully the gratitude I feel towards you by making excuses for Kagha. My choice was clear.
But... something's different. You're aware of the monster inside you. You don't bow to the Absolute, like the True Souls do...
As for the idol? It's nothing compared to a life. A mere object, next to one of nature's creations.
Soon. Remember the dangers I told you about - there'll be plenty of time to face them.
Neither of us saw what happened before - maybe the child's death wasn't her fault.
I was an unwilling guest of the goblins - but your efforts left them in disarray and I was able to escape.
The fire of ambition is in her very blood - and cruel blood is a life companion.
Instead, I shall listen to the explanation that you owe me.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'I'm going to give you a chance to say your piece'

Text.Value: You'll have your hands full with her. She shows great spirit, to put it mildly.
...That problem. You're infected with the mind flayer spawn, aren't you? Oak Father preserve you, child.
You should turn her over to my kin for judgement. Bad blood still lingers.
But that's tomorrow's problem. Take some time for yourself tonight - rest, celebrate. Come morning, I'll be by your side.
The journey to Moonrise Towers, and all the dangers that that entails.
A misjudgement - one that should weigh heavily upon her. But the grove still needs her passion.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaining his reasoning to the player

Text.Value: Now get out of my sight. There is nothing more to be said.
Now get out of my sight. There is nothing more to be said.
I will do what I can to help you. Let us speak tomorrow - you and I both have matters to see to first.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'I'll help - but not quite yet'

Text.Value: She shows great insolence. But time will humble her - and the grove still needs her.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'I'll make a druid of Kagha yet'
